There’s also an information-theoretic way to think about it.

Imagine two people.

Person A has never studied calculus.

Person B has.

If you write:

\int_a^b f(x)\,dx

Person A receives a few marks on paper.

Person B reconstructs an entire conceptual landscape.

The same signal produced radically different internal models.

That tells us the information isn’t entirely in the symbol or entirely in the mind—it’s in the interaction between the two.

